      <div xml:id="NA40-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaṭkup (ET: /; ETv: talaivikkup) pāṅkāyiṉār kēṭpap parattaic colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the other woman said to HER when the people close [to her] were listening.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA40">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            neṭunā voṇmaṇi kaṭimaṉai yiraṭṭak</l>
<l>            kuraiyilaip pōkiya viravumaṇaṟ pantarp</l>
<l>            perumpāṇ kāval pūṇṭeṉa vorucārt</l>
<l>            tiruntiḻai makaḷir viricci niṟpa</l>
<l>            veṟiyuṟa virinta vaṟuvai mellaṇaip </l>
<l>            puṉiṟunāṟu ceviliyoṭu putalvaṉ ṟuñca</l>
<l>            vaiyavi yaṇinta neyyāṭ ṭīraṇip</l>
<l>            pacuney kūrnta meṉmai yākkaic</l>
<l>            cīrkeḻu maṭantai yīrimai porunta</l>
<l>            naḷḷeṉ kaṅkuṟ kaḷvaṉ pōla </l>
<l>            vakaṉṟuṟai yūraṉum vantaṉaṉ</l>
<l>            ciṟantōṉ peyaraṉ piṟanta māṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

<l rend="indent">While long-tongued bright bells sound in the protected house,</l>
<l rend="indent2">because<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pūṇṭeṉa</term> presumably has to be understood as a causal clause, though it is not clear at all what could be reasoned for here. K.P. (based on N.I.) translates a comparison, but I for one do not see this in the text.</note> protection has been made by a great tune in the arbour</l>
<l rend="indent2">[spread with] mixed sand where rustling(?) leaves are</l>
<l rend="indent3">moving(?)<note place="foot">What to make of <term xml:lang="ta">pōkiya</term> here?</note> on one side(?),</l>
<l>women with perfect jewels are standing</l>
<l rend="indent3">[listening to] auspicious voices.</l>
<l>The man from the village with wide ghats has come too,</l>
<l rend="indent3">like a robber in deepest night,</l>
<l rend="indent">when the weighty<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cīḻkeḻu</term> most probably refers to HER new social status: by giving birth to a male child, she has attained a new position in the house.</note> girl joined [her] moist lids,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with [her] soft body cooled with green oil, adorned</l>
<l rend="indent2">with moistness in an oil bath, adorned with white mustard,</l>
<l rend="indent">while [her] son sleeps with [his] foster-mother, fragrant of new</l>
<l rend="indent">birth, on the bed with soft cloth spread out to have perfume(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">veṟi-y-uṟa</term> is a problem here. The usual <term xml:lang="ta">Veṟi</term> dance is out of the question, and the commentatorial "perfume" is not evident in this context, to say the least (for <term xml:lang="ta">veṟi</term> in that sense see, however, note on NA 308.6). The variant <term xml:lang="ta">veḷi</term> ("spread out to be outside") appears to be an attempt to make sense, however likely it might seem that a newly born child is brought to sleep outside the house.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">– because<note place="foot">It is difficult to choose between the variants <term xml:lang="ta">māṟu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">āṟu</term>, one causal and one temporal, but both amounting to the same.</note> one is born who bears the name of [his] elder<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṟantōṉ</term> probably refers to the continuation of the lineage (superior in a temporal sense). As usual, these cultural details are far too allusive to get a grip at.</note>.</l>
        </lg>
